# What actually deviates right now (and how to fix)

## 1) Patterns with a slash (e.g. `a/b/`) don’t match directories

**Symptom**
Directory-only patterns that contain a slash (e.g. `a/b/`) won’t match the directory because `matchesDirectoryPath` returns `false` for non-rooted slash patterns. In Git, when the `.gitignore` is at repo root (your constraint), *any* pattern containing a slash is anchored to root and should be matched against the full path.

**Fix (surgical change)**
Update `matchesDirectoryPath` to treat **any** pattern containing `/` as anchored to the root (i.e., match the full directory path). Today it only considers `p.rooted`.

```go
// BEFORE (conceptual)
func matchesDirectoryPath(p pattern, dirPath string) bool {
    if p.rooted {
        return matchGlob(p, dirPath)
    }
    if !strings.Contains(p.pattern, "/") {
        return matchGlob(p, path.Base(dirPath))
    }
    // currently returns false here for non-rooted slash patterns
    return false
}

// AFTER (drop the early return; anchor slash-patterns to root)
func matchesDirectoryPath(p pattern, dirPath string) bool {
    if p.rooted || strings.Contains(p.pattern, "/") {
        // In our “single root .gitignore” world, slash ⇒ anchored to repo root
        return matchGlob(p, dirPath)
    }
    // No slash ⇒ compare against the basename only
    return matchGlob(p, path.Base(dirPath))
}
```

**Why this matters**

* Positive `a/b/` must ignore `a/b` (dir) and everything within.
* Negated `!a/b/` must unignore that exact directory (subject to parent-exclusion semantics).
* Your parent-exclusion prepass (`findExcludedParentDirectories`) already uses full-path matching for slash patterns; this change makes the second pass consistent.

